About: As the world becomes globalized, today’s companies expect to hire graduates who can be effective in a global environment. In this course, students will learn about the different aspects and examples of cultural similiarities and differences in a personal and professional setting, as well as the theories of intercultural communication and how to apply them in real world situations. Students will also learn about Irish culture and history from local experts and be able to develop an appreciation for the culture of their host country. Students may be placed in either Dublin or Galway, depending on the best internship placement for their field of study. On the ground support and cultural activities will be provided for students in both locations.

Name: UF in Ireland - Sports and Healthcare
About: Come explore and learn about sports medicine in historic Dublin. Students will gain a broader perspective on global healthcare, particularly in sports medicine. Ireland has a Universal Healthcare System and is one of the few countries in the world that has an International Arrangement for the profession of Athletic Training. Students will earn 6 credits for ATR2010 (Prevention and Care; required course for APK majors) and ATR4018 (Professionalism and Communication in Sports Healthcare). Students will visit sports facilities, interact with sports medicine professionals, and engage in cultural opportunities. This program is designed for pre-health students of all types and majors.

Name: UF in Istanbul - Urban Studies from the Perspective of the Global South
About: This six-week study abroad program aims to guide students towards a deep understanding of global urban dynamics in a uniquely vibrant, exciting, complex and historical metropolis of the Global South: Istanbul. Students will experience the ways in which Istanbul succeeds in being a cosmopolitan bridge between the East and West (a metropolis of rare sociality, a sophisticated site of art and culture, and an urban identity of politesse and civility), as well as the ways it fails to achieve other global metropolitan standards (its urban poor and marginalized populations, scarred earth and polluted air, and inhabitants burdened by various problems). Through immersive experiences and critical exploration, students will create life-long memories in one of the most captivating cities at the crossroads of global urban life.

Name: UF in Italy - Animal Science in Italy
About: This program was designed with Animal Science majors in mind, with a focus on animal production and management, profitability, and the role of culture as it relates to food production. Students will be directly exposed to farmers, cheese makers, animal science professors, students, and laypeople in Italy. The program includes several technical visits, in which students will have tours of various farms and lectures on their production systems. Then students will do tastings, discussions, and reflections after each visit. The program also includes guest speakers at different Italian Universities, in which UF students will listen to top-notch Italian scientists and have an opportunity to discuss and interact with them.

Name: UF in Italy - Automotive Industries to Urban Planning
About: This program aims to introduce students to the surface transportation system and its components, including automotive engineering principles, and to compare and contrast two different types of systems: that of the US and that of Italy.  The program will offer UF students the opportunity to experience a very different transportation system abroad, while learning about the three main components of the transportation system: vehicles, travelers, and the environment.   The students will learn about principles of traffic engineering and urban planning as they will be experiencing the implementation of these principles in Italy, where pedestrians, bicycles, and vehicles are well integrated into the urban environment.  The program will also provide the opportunity to learn about and experience the automobile manufacturing and advanced vehicle electronics and other technologies in Italy’s Motor Valley. The curriculum will leverage the students’ lived in experience of the Italian transportation system and will allow them to understand the advantages and disadvantages of different systems by contrasting the US system with that of Italy.  Experiencing the Italian transportation system within the day-to-day activities of the class will provide students a unique perspective, which will be reinforced through daily lessons. Students will participate in lectures and group projects focused on transportation and automotive engineering.

Name: UF in Italy - Clinical Shadowing
About: Shadow physicians in a hospital in Italy for 20 hours per week in partnership with the Atlantis program. Students will rotate through multiple departments in the local hospital, observing physicians and residents in a variety of medical fields. The online internship course will allow students to reflect on their experiences. Each week students will also participate in a 1 day cultural excursion in the region, enjoying the beauty of Italy and learning about Italian culture.

Name: UF in Italy - Food Production to Consumption
About: Earn 3 credits studying the art and science behind Italian food from production to consumption. The course will cover important aspects of production of classical Italian foods and food systems in Italy. You will visit a variety of agricultural areas including grape, wine, olive, vegetable, wheat and deciduous crop regions, as well as dairy and cheese-making regions. You will see, study, and taste many of these products as you are guided by the owners of these enterprises on comprehensive tours. You will also immerse yourself in the centuries' old Italian cultures and customs. There will be ample opportunity to meet local farmers and vintners and enjoy each region's unique cuisine.

Name: UF in Italy - History of Sustainable Construction
About: This program provides an overview of the history of infrastructure construction techniques in Europe with an emphasis on Italian techniques. The integration of international sustainable practices will be evaluated and demonstrated through literature review, lectures, and site tours. The methods for practical application of the European techniques on US construction sites, will be incorporated into all presentations. Highlights of the program include interaction with ancient sites relative to sustainable construction techniques such as Colosseum, Apian Way, aqueducts, and Roman Forum;  understanding the impact of the Renaissance on the sustainable practices; and influences of current climate change on construction.

Name: UF in Italy - Human Performance
About: This program takes place in Florence, and Rome. Students will have the opportunity to participate in guided cultural excursions throughout their stay in each city and lectures will often take place at historical sites. The location is ideally suited for all majors in the College of Health and Human Performance, and the program is open to all majors. Students that have an interest in travel, Italian culture, tourism, sport management, or kinesiology are especially encouraged to apply.

Name: UF in Japan - Applied Japanese Technology and Methods in Built Environment
About: Experience the transformative UF in Japan program, where students have the incredible opportunity to immerse themselves in the exploration of Japan's unique approach to the design, procurement, and delivery of the built environment. Embracing the essence of minimalism and uncluttered spaces, the program is dedicated to honing in on the principles of functionality, efficiency, and practicality, while also delving into how Japanese architecture has evolved to withstand natural and artificial disasters. Gain profound insight into the post-WW II development of Japan's built environment while delving into the fascinating cultural disparities between the US and Japan. Understand how cultural activities impact society's perceptions of the engineering and construction industries and explore the impact of Japanese management philosophies on global manufacturing practices and cultural norms. Venture through three major cities via the renowned bullet train, with each city offering unique and enriching learning opportunities. This program is designed for students of design, engineering, and construction, and also welcomes individuals interested in the captivating intricacies of Japanese culture and its emphasis on cultural harmony and quality. Whether you're a design aficionado or a culture enthusiast, this course is open to any Sophomore or higher-level undergraduate student eager to delve into these compelling topics. Join us for an unforgettable journey into the heart of Japan's captivating built environment and culture.

Name: UF in Japan - Business Consulting and Cross-Cultural Communication
About: As the world’s third-largest economy, Japan plays a significant role in global trade, finance, and technological innovation. With its cutting-edge advancements in technology, renewable energy, and healthcare, Japanese companies lead the way in automation, robotics, and AI, significantly shaping the future of industries around the globe. A comprehensive understanding of Japanese business dynamics requires navigating the intricate relationship between the country’s cultural heritage, which profoundly impacts its business landscape. This six-week program offers both business and non-business students a unique opportunity to immerse themselves in Japan’s rich culture while gaining valuable insights into its dynamic business environment. Students will have the chance to visit leading companies, attend expert panels, and collaborate in teams to develop innovative solutions to real-world challenges faced by multinational organizations.  To further enrich this educational experience, students will engage in various cultural events that provide firsthand insights into Japan's vibrant traditions and business practices. Both courses are taught in English, and no prior knowledge of the Japanese language is required. This program is ideal for students interested in experiences that blend traditional cultural values with modern innovations. Additionally, it is designed to enhance global perspectives, critical thinking, communication, and presentation skills, preparing students for success in a globalized business world.

Name: UF in Japan - Cross-Cultural Engineering and Design
About: This program focuses on building cross-cultural design skills through practice and immersion in daily life in Kyoto. Our student-explorers will investigate the rich history and culture of Japan, see how our environments mold our behaviors, and refine their perspective by seeing the world through the perspective of a different culture. This refinement of cultural understanding - the ability to see the world through the eyes of others - can help us design and build artifacts that improve the lives of others from all parts of the globe.

Name: UF in Japan - Japanese Culture in Place
About: Japan is a country known as much for anime as for its Zen temples, Harajuku fashion as much as samurai castles. Are you interested in learning about the culture of this fascinating nation? The Department of Languages, Literatures, and Cultures offers an intensive four-week study abroad experience in Tokyo and Kyoto during Summer A. Students will visit a variety of culturally significant sites and engage in various cultural activities while studying the historical and cultural significance of those sites and the city around them. Students will gain new insights into Japanese culture and valuable experience living in a foreign culture and society. The course is taught in English, and is not designed as a language study abroad program (although learners of Japanese will, of course, have ample opportunities to use their language abilities). The class is divided into three parts: Tokyo, Kyoto, and online work back home. Students will spend two weeks each in Tokyo and Kyoto. Tokyo is Japan’s modern capital, while Kyoto is Japan’s ancient capital. These two cities offer a wide variety of historically and culturally significant sites to visit and activities to enjoy. Students will learn about and visit modern hubs of fashion and pop culture like Akihabara and Harajuku, famous preserves of traditional culture such as Kiyomizu Temple and Tōdai-ji, and politically charged sites like Yasukuni shrine and the Imperial palace. Students will then complete a project after returning home, before the end of the Summer A session.

Name: UF in Japan - Japanese Sport and Culture
About: Sport. is. global. This is true both from a business perspective and cultural perspective. In this program will study the sport industry and the sport experience as it exists globally (beyond the United States) through the Japanese context. You will examine historical and contemporary cultural elements of sport in the US and Japan. You will use the outcomes from both courses to be able to solve contemporary global challenges in both sport management and social issues in sport. This program will expose you to the management of sport in a country whose sport structures are very different than the United States but are like much of the rest of the world. You will interact with representatives from a ministry of sport, professional sport teams, Olympic sport, and businesses that market to a Japanese audience. You will also experience sport as it is embedded deeply in Japanese culture, via various spaces: sumo, kendo, high school sport, and their unique relationship with baseball. In exploring the management and cultural side of sport simultaneously, you will connect industry with social structures, and will more greatly acknowledge the intersections among business, organizations, and culture in any society (including our own). This new knowledge will prepare you to analyze the complex challenges you will face in any industry, either locally or globally. Exploring the connection between culture and sport in a real setting allows you to examine the phenomenon of culture more broadly. You will see how social practices (such as sport) are informed by communal values and evolve through collective understanding. This realization and exposure will create room to more greatly appreciate different cultures and world views, and to become more aware of the reality of your own culture and cultural world view. This program can be useful for any major but will be particularly enriching for those interested in the management of sport either domestically or internationally, those interested in international business, and those studying Asian cultures.

Name: UF in Japan - Medicine Microbiology and Health
About: Embark on a transformative journey with the University of Florida's "Microbiology, Medicine, Health, and Wellness Study Abroad Program" in Japan! This unique program is designed to broaden your understanding of medicine and healthcare while immersing you in the rich cultural tapestry of Japan. Explore Tokyo's cutting-edge medical research facilities, uncover the ancient traditions of Kyoto, and dive into the serene beauty of Nara, all while gaining unparalleled insights into Japan's healthcare system. Our program offers an extraordinary opportunity to trace the evolution of Japanese medical practices, from traditional methods to modern innovations. As you compare and contrast the medical practices and healthcare systems of Asia and North America, you'll gain a global perspective that is essential in today's interconnected world. A highlight of the program is the deep dive into fermentation and gut health. Learn about Japan's time-honored fermentation techniques and their cutting-edge applications in modern medicine and nutrition. Additionally, you'll explore the Okinawa Blue Zone, renowned for its residents' longevity. Investigate the diet, lifestyle, and social practices of this unique region and discover how these can inform global health and wellness strategies. Cultural competence is at the heart of this program. By immersing yourself in Japan's healthcare system and understanding its cultural context, you'll develop a nuanced understanding of how cultural factors shape patient care—a crucial skill in the globalized medical field. The program also offers invaluable professional networking opportunities, including internships and connections with Japanese healthcare professionals, setting the stage for future collaborations and career growth.

Name: UF in Japan - Pharmacy (PharmJapan)
About: This program is reserved for PharmD students. Please contact Randall Doty for more information.

Name: UF in Kenya - Ecology of East African Savannas
About: Travel to East Africa this summer to study the ecology and conservation of savanna ecosystems! For three weeks, you'll live in some of the most beautiful and wild areas of East Africa, experiencing first-hand the extraordinary biological and cultural diversity of the region. Over the course of our program, you'll learn about the ecology and conservation of tropical ecosystems, while gaining valuable field experience through participation in scientific fieldwork, conservation initiatives and interactions with ecologists and conservation biologists in the region. As human populations increase, people and wildlife have come increasingly into contact--and often conflict. In Laikipia, as in much of Africa, most of these conflicts occur outside of formally protected wildlife areas, and considerable controversy exists over how to effectively avoid or resolve them. Reconciling how, simultaneously, to protect and conserve wildlife populations while supporting human economic growth and cultural diversity is one of the greatest challenges faced by conservationists today. To grapple with the human-wildlife conflict in East Africa, our program focuses on three interrelated goals. First, team members will experience firsthand Kenya's extraordinary natural landscapes, and learn the tools and skills necessary to evaluate the health, functioning and integrity of the ecosystems we encounter. Participants will hone their skills of scientific observation and learn key ecological and wildlife monitoring methods. Armed with these skills, our team will conduct a variety of student-led research projects, enriching our understanding of he principles and practice of wildlife ecology and conservation. A second goal of our program will be to understand the human dimension of the human-wildlife conflict through first-hand experiences with local people whose livelihood depends on the land. Exposure to local people and their perspectives will give us perspectives on the fascinating human dimension of this culturally rich region of East Africa. In-depth crosscultural exchange and dialogue with area residents will educate us about the needs and concerns of local people, as well as the historical, economic and cultural constraints under which they operate. A third goal of our program will be to integrate our understanding of the human, scientific and wildlife dimensions of Kenya's conservation crisis.

Name: UF in Lille - Engineering and Arts in France
About: This program offers you a unique opportunity to learn Physics 2 at the Université Catholique de Lille (Catholic University of Lille) in France while exploring the rich history of art and engineering practices. You will learn the importance of Science, Technology, Engineering, Arts, and Mathematics (STEAM) in the historical and cultural city of Lille.

Name: UF in Lille - Overseas Studies in Sociology
About: This study abroad will take us to Lille, France, a vibrant, urban center with a student population of over 150,000. Lille’s diversity and location provide sociologists an ideal cross-cultural context for studying the causes, consequences, implications and meaning of human behavior. Through lectures, site visits, engagement with the visual and performing arts, and local and international excursions, we will develop a deeper awareness of our own cultural identities while learning about the nature of social relationships, structures, and inequalities within other European societies. Our UF course, SYP3510 Deviance and Social Control, addresses the central question: What is deviance and how can we understand it as a socially constructed phenomenon? Students will select a second course, offered by our host institution, Université Catholique de Lille, from a range of possibilities in the areas of French culture and history, political science and law, health and healthcare systems, sustainability studies, and business and communication.

Name: UF in Lima - MIB GIE
About: Please note: This program is only open to approved MIB/graduate business students.

Name: UF in Limerick - Study and Intern
About: Spend a semester studying and working in Limerick, Ireland's fifth largest city. Classes will be taken at the University of Limerick. The University of Limerick is in the top 2% of universities in the world. It is an independent, internationally focused university with a proud record of innovation in education and excellence in research and scholarship. Located on the west coast of Ireland along the picturesque River Shannon, students enjoy an unspoiled natural environment blended with state-of-the-art teaching and research facilities. On their award winning campus students can study in a safe and supportive environment. The University of Limerick has been voted number one in the world for student experience. This program brings the traditional semester abroad journey to the next level by providing students with academic, professional and personal exposure and experience in one of the world’s best study abroad locations.

Name: UF in Lippe - Construction Management
About: The program was developed so that participating University of Florida students, as well as graduate or undergraduate students from other universities, and the Interior Architecture, Architecture, and Construction Engineering students of the OWL University of Applied Sciences and Arts (TH OWL) in Germany could benefit from the mutual exchange of knowledge. German interior architecture and architecture students from the Detmold School of Architecture and Interior Architecture participate in the program by enrolling in regular courses offered in the Department of Interior Design, Department of Construction Engineering students enroll in regular courses offered in the Rinker School of Construction Management and UF students (and other university students) participate in this summer program in Germany. As part of this program students attend lectures, workshops, laboratory studies and visit various locations to observe different design and construction processes, techniques, and methods used in Germany. Students will also learn about the history of Germany, its government, the culture and social norms of Germans, and construction practices in Germany. In addition, UF students see many points of interest that are of historical, cultural, or architectural/environmental importance. The program consists of a 4-week stay organized by the Department of Civil Engineering. The program will start with a joint welcome day (with students participating in the program of the Detmold School of Architecture and Interior Architecture) to get to know the Campus and City of Detmold and include more opportunities for joint activities in the following weeks. All instruction is in English. Lectures are offered on different topics of interest and will be supplemented by excursions and discussions onsite.

Name: UF in Lippe - Interior Design
About: The program was developed so that participating University of Florida students, as well as graduate or undergraduate students from other universities, and the Interior Architecture, Architecture, and Construction Engineering students of the Technical University Ostwestfalen-Lippe (TH OWL) in Germany could benefit from the mutual exchange of design knowledge. German interior architecture and architecture students from the Detmolder Schule für Architektur and Innernarchitektur participate in the program by enrolling in regular courses offered in the Department of Interior Design, and UF students (and other university students) participate in this summer program in Germany. As part of this program students attend lectures and visit various locations to observe different design processes, techniques, and methods used in Germany. Students will also learn about the history of Germany, its government, the culture and social norms of Germans, preservation techniques, restoration efforts, and construction practices in Germany. In addition, UF students see many points of interest that are of historical, cultural, or architectural importance. The 6-week program also includes completion of a design studio project that utilizes cutting edge lab facilities and additional design firm and industry tours. All instruction is in English. Lectures are offered on many different topics of interest, but much of the learning and enjoyment of this exchange lies in experiencing the places that are visited.

Name: UF in Lisbon - Journalism and Communications
About: This study abroad program combines academics with an authentic foreign travel experience. CJC in Portugal offers students a unique opportunity to immerse themselves in the rich culture, history, and natural beauty of Portugal. The itinerary includes visits to iconic sites, breathtaking landscapes, and engaging cultural events in both Lisbon and Porto.

Name: UF in Lisbon - SFMBA
About: Please note: This program is only open to approved MBA/graduate business students.

Name: UF in London - CLAS Internship
About: The London CLAS Internship offers students in the College of Liberal Arts and Sciences an opportunity to take courses in the humanities and social sciences, along with completing an internship. Internships in a wide variety of areas will help you develop the skills you learn as a Liberal Arts and Sciences student and apply them in the workplace. Major and/or minor courses are offered in Economics, English, History, Political Science, Psychology, Sociology, Sustainability Studies, and Women’s Studies. Pre-Law students are also encouraged to apply. Students in colleges other than CLAS, or with interest in pursuing a Business major or minor, should apply through the College of Business’s UF in London Study and Intern Program.

Name: UF in London - Study and Intern
About: The Warrington College of Business offers a study abroad program in London that provides students a magnificent life experience - all while earning UF credits! Business and *non-business courses are available. In addition, this program presents a unique opportunity for students to complete an international internship while studying in London. Enjoy theatre, great museums, and exciting nightlife in one of the most cosmopolitan and culturally diverse cities in Europe. When will you have another opportunity to spend an entire semester in one of the world's most historic locations?

Name: UF in London - Technological Applications for Disability Access
About: This program is designed for UF students from all fields of study to learn about disability access in London and the role of technology in facilitating access for all citizens. The program is a partnership between the UF Disability Resource Center (DRC) and Herbert Wertheim College of Engineering (HWCOE) to give students the opportunity to learn about the role of technologies in increasing access for people living with disabilities, as well as the use of policy and advocacy for social change. Students will get to explore London and learn about the challenges and opportunities associate with disability access in urban environments. Students will visit organizations advocating for people with disabilities, technological and infrastructure companies pioneering smart cities technology in urban planning, mass transportation, and autonomous vehicles. Students will also visit iconic landmarks in London and experience British culture in the two week program. There will be a week of virtual discussions before and after the program to facilitate pre-departure and post-program conversations.

Name: UF in London - Vampire and Empire London
About: Vampire and Empire London will discuss the setting of Bram Stoker’s signature novel, located in London. It will follow its rich trajectory in cinema, history and literature, and discuss its multifaceted and enduring cultural impact. Lectures related to the novel and its historical context, London, will take place on sites such as the Highgate Cemetery, the Tower of London, the Freud Museum, the Jewish Museum, the Museum of Science, British Museum, St. Paul Cathedral, for on-location instruction and on-site learning.  British Imperial politics will be discussed on location of some of the renowned places of Imperial learning, museums or landscapes, such as the Greenwich Royal Observatory and Museum, Victoria and Albert Museum, Madame Tussauds, The Royal College of Physicians, the Buckingham Palace Gardens, Natural History Museum. These visits and the class instruction will provide students with in-depth knowledge of the city of London and its rich cultural, literary and political history.  Students will spend the first week of the six week program in Gainesville preparing for their five weeks abroad.

Name: UF in Madrid - Business Language and Culture
About: Enjoy delectable tapas, great museums, and exciting nightlife in one of the most historic and culturally vibrant cities in Europe. When will you have another opportunity to spend an entire semester in this cosmopolitan location? The Warrington College of Business offers a study abroad program in Madrid that provides students a magnificent life experience - all while earning UF credits! Business and non-business courses are available, with particular emphasis on Spanish language and culture.

Name: UF in Maynooth - Innovation Academy
About: In Ireland, a country where innovation, inventiveness, and opportunity abound, you will see how the Irish have tackled some of their most challenging environmental and economic problems. In this program, we will explore how the richly traditional Ireland continues to influence the thriving culture of her people. To best study this, students will earn credit for IDS 1940: Creativity and Design Thinking for Innovation & IDS 4930: Innovotators Mindset. These courses will focus on innovation in business and on the work of social entrepreneurs in Ireland. Along with the classes, you will travel across Ireland, where you will visit start-up and major businesses, innovation programs, and many cultural sites.

Name: UF in Merida - Tropical Ecology and Spanish
About: Experience life in tropical Mexico. Hike through caves. Sleep in a hammock. Visit ancient Maya archaeological sites. Travel to contemporary Maya villages. See monkeys, crocodiles, sea turtles, and flamingoes. Take a boat trip through the mangroves. Sample Yucatecan cuisine. Hear new music. Dance to exotic rhythms. Live with a Mexican family in the beautiful, modern city of Mérida. Experience all this and more through the University of Florida/Autonomous University of Yucatán (UADY) Summer B Program in Mérida, Yucatán, Mexico. You will receive 3 credits for Spanish, 3 credits for Tropical Ecology, and 2 credits for Humans & the Environment of the Yucatan Peninsula. Join us for fun classes and weekly fieldtrips and have an unforgettable summer! Gain an Understanding of the Structure and Function of Ecosystems on the Yucatán Peninsula. Develop Conversational Spanish Ability. Integrate into Mexican Life Through Daily Interactions with a Host Family and Local University Students.

Name: UF in Morocco - Arab Culture Life & Traditions
About: UF in Morocco - Arab Culture, Life, and Traditions will offer students a comprehensive journey into the rich tapestry of Arabic culture, spanning its linguistic diversity, historical evolution, societal structures, and cherished traditions. Through a series of thematic modules, students will delve into various facets of Arab culture, gaining insights into its complexities, dynamics, and contemporary developments. This month-long program is split between two different Moroccan cities - the first two weeks will take place in Tangier, and the final two weeks in Marrakech.

Name: UF in North Queensland - Sustaining Humans and their Environment
About: This program offers an interdisciplinary approach to sustaining human societies in their natural environments. You will spend much of your time out in the field, visiting and observing Australia firsthand with local field guides and UF professors with expertise in the field related to sustainability.

Name: UF in Osnabrueck - Sustainability and Innovation in Engineering and Planning
About: Earn six credits through this interdisciplinary program that enables students to enhance their knowledge in engineering, life sciences, and planning processes and combine it with hands-on lab work and company visits. The students benefit from the application-oriented and interdisciplinary approach of Osnabrück University of Applied Sciences to address and solve major problems on the way to a sustainable use of natural resources and innovative development.

Name: UF in Panama - Exploring the Canal Across Disciplines
About: The UF in Panama program is a 8-day immersive program designed to help students develop both personally and professionally. This experiential journey combines cultural exploration and career readiness activities with a focus on empowering first-generation students and building their social capital. The program will draw lessons from one of the wonders of the modern world, the Panama Canal. Students will learn about the canal from multiple perspectives relevant to each college, highlighting the interdisciplinary nature of complex global problems. The program also seeks to empower students to explore potential career pathways by offering direct exposure to employers and companies in Panama. These hands-on experiences and networking opportunities enable students to envision and prepare for diverse professional futures. Lastly, the program fosters expanded social capital by facilitating interaction with peers, faculty, and professionals. This enhances academic and career readiness, as well as cultural competency in our interconnected world.

Name: UF in Panama - Impacts on the Panama Canal
About: This program provides an opportunity for students who major in engineering, construction management, history, Latin America studies, and other diverse fields to study abroad in Panama and see first-hand the impact of engineering works on society and the environment. This project will use asynchronous videos and existing materials at the University of Florida Panama Canal Museum for 1-2 weeks before the in-country visit to educate students on Panamanian history, construction methods used in the canal construction, and societal impacts. Students will learn about the biodiversity, economic, and societal circumstances present during the canal construction and impacts of the canal locally and globally on the society, economy, and environment, including the effects of climate change on canal operations.

Name: UF in Paris - African Americans in Paris
About: This course will explore the African American presence in Paris. Students will receive information about three groups of Black Americans who have traveled to Paris. These groups include: political persons, academic figures and cultural bearers. During the week students will visit several historic sites in Paris where the individuals that students have studied lived and worked.

Name: UF in Paris - Business Language and Culture
About: Enjoy French cuisine, great museums, and stunning architecture in one of the most remarkable cities in Europe. When will you have another opportunity to spend an entire semester in one of the world's most historic locations? The Warrington College of Business offers a study abroad program in Paris that provides students a magnificent life experience - all while earning UF credits! Business and non-business courses are available, with particular emphasis on French language and culture. In addition, this program presents a unique opportunity for students proficient in French to complete an international internship while studying in Paris.

Name: UF in Paris - Culture & Language in Context
About: Through two complementary courses entirely taught in French, you will be immersed not only in the French language but also in contemporary French culture and art. The course FRE 3224 invites you to explore France’s gastronomy, cinema, politics, industries, small and major businesses. In the course FRW 3930, you will discover the rich cultural and artistic heritage of the City of Lights through visits to museums, parks and gardens, iconic monuments and neighborhoods. Both of these courses can count towards the UF major or minor in French and Francophone Studies. The program offers several academic and cultural excursions that will further immerse you into French culture, including an overnight trip to Normandy and Brittany (Mont-Saint Michel and Saint-Malo) and a day trip to Champagne (Reims).

Name: UF in Paris - Musical Context Aesthetics and Practice
About: This program offers students an understanding of the many facets of musical life in Paris, such as musical instrument and accessories manufacturing, music teaching, and performing as well the chance to put current practices in perspective by exploring historical contexts. The primary audience for this program is saxophonists interested in the history of the saxophone, saxophone manufacturing, and especially saxophone teaching and general musical performance in France. Others interested in music and the inner workings of the music industry and the development of and professional lives of musicians are also welcome.

Name: UF in Peru - Ancient and Modern Built Environment
About: This program aims to provide students with a broad understanding of design and construction practices in Peru, focusing on the preservation of ancient structures and the influence of topography, climate, and culture on architectural design. Students will be provided with cultural immersion experiences that enhance their communication abilities and interpersonal skills while fostering an appreciation for the importance of preserving historical heritage for future generations.

Name: UF in Prague - European Studies
About: The Center for European Studies offers you an opportunity to make degree progress while exploring life in one of the most enchanting European capitals. Featured courses contextualize subject matter vis-à-vis your immediate surroundings: The UF course offers an introduction to the politics, history, and culture of East Central Europe in the 20th and 21st centuries, with a focus on Prague and the Czech Republic.  The local course provides an opportunity to explore Prague in depth as a center of European art and culture over several centuries.  Most courses taken in Prague count toward the Minor or Certificate in East-Central European Studies (ECES) or European Union Studies (EUS).

Name: UF in Purpan - European Agriculture Food Chains & French Culture
About: Join one of UF's most unique exchange programs in southern France. Get hands on experience in agriculture, specifically in Food Resource Economics, Animal Sciences and Viticulture! This unique program also provides students with an internship in which they will stay with a host family and work on their farm as part of the exchange. Due to this internship portion, we suggest that students be mentally and physically willing and able to work long days in an agricultural setting.

Name: UF in Quito - Supporting Children Families and Education
About: This program will allow you to explore and further your knowledge of Latin American life, history, politics, and education in a highly immersive environment in one of the most biodiverse areas of the world – the middle of the Earth! Through coursework and site visits, you will become more knowledgeable about issues affecting Latin America, particularly in Ecuador, related to education and access spanning the Andes regions to the shores of the Pacific Ocean. You will analyze issues such as families and children, social supports, early education settings, and interventions available to communities in the economic hub of Quito to rural, indigenous regions in the Andes Mountains, to remote eco-locations in the Galapagos Islands. The program will include activities & assignments to foster the integration of experiential & academic learning and to help students apply their global understanding of social and education-related issues in their future endeavors.

Name: UF in Rio - Language and Culture
About: The University of Florida Language and Culture Program in Rio de Janeiro is a 6-week FLAS-certified program offering 140 contact hours of classroom instruction in Portuguese. Designed with ACTFL standards in mind, the classes and assignments are based on the 5 “C’s” of Language Learning:  Communication, Culture, Communities, Comparisons and Connections. Hence, all classroom activities and assignments involve intensive language instruction in Portuguese. The program offers three levels: intermediate, advanced intermediate and advanced, plus a cultural component for all levels.

Name: UF in Rome - Business Language and Culture
About: Enjoy incredible food, great museums, and ancient sites in one of the historic cities in Europe. When will you have another opportunity to spend an entire semester in this remarkable location? The Warrington College of Business offers a study abroad program in Rome that provides students a magnificent life experience - all while earning UF credits! Business and non-business courses are available, with particular emphasis on Italian language and culture.

Name: UF in Rome - Language and Culture
About: This six-week Summer B program offers courses in Italian language, Italian Cinema and Culture, and Roman History. In existence since 1995, this classic UF study abroad experience is open to (and attracts) students of all majors! No prior experience with Italian is required. Our program provides a panorama of life in Rome from antiquity to the present day. Course content centers on the countless monuments, museums, and other treasures found in every corner of the city. Students will experience first-hand what they have seen and discussed in lectures. The Eternal City is our classroom!

Name: UF in Salzburg - Business
About: UF in Salzburg offers programs in Music, European Studies, and Business and is open to all majors. Music majors and minors may take private lessons, music history and/or arranging. The European Studies program provides major credit for History and Political Science majors. Experience the European way of life as well as the European culture, arts, and business worlds. Salzburg is considered by many to be one of the most beautiful cities in Europe. With a population of about 150,000, Salzburg is situated in the heart of Europe on the northern edge of the eastern Alps right at the Austrian-German border. Surrounded by picturesque mountains, the city still mirrors in its historical center – a declared UNESCO World Heritage Site - more than a thousand years of European history and culture. Its rich and vibrant cultural heritage is reflected in concerts, festivals and a great variety of events throughout the year.

Name: UF in Salzburg - European Studies
About: UF in Salzburg offers programs in Music, European Studies, and Business and is open to all majors. Music majors and minors may take private lessons, music history and/or arranging. The European Studies program provides major credit for History and Political Science majors. Experience the European way of life as well as the European culture, arts, and business worlds. Salzburg is considered by many to be one of the most beautiful cities in Europe. With a population of about 150,000, Salzburg is situated in the heart of Europe on the northern edge of the eastern Alps right at the Austrian-German border. Surrounded by picturesque mountains, the city still mirrors in its historical center – a declared UNESCO World Heritage Site - more than a thousand years of European history and culture. Its rich and vibrant cultural heritage is reflected in concerts, festivals and a great variety of events throughout the year.

Name: UF in Salzburg - Music
About: UF in Salzburg offers programs in Music, European Studies, and Business and is open to all majors. Music majors and minors may take private lessons, music history and/or arranging. The European Studies program provides major credit for History and Political Science majors. Experience the European way of life as well as the European culture, arts, and business worlds. Salzburg is considered by many to be one of the most beautiful cities in Europe. With a population of about 150,000, Salzburg is situated in the heart of Europe on the northern edge of the eastern Alps right at the Austrian-German border. Surrounded by picturesque mountains, the city still mirrors in its historical center – a declared UNESCO World Heritage Site - more than a thousand years of European history and culture. Its rich and vibrant cultural heritage is reflected in concerts, festivals and a great variety of events throughout the year.

Name: UF in Santiago - MSRE
About: Please note: This is a closed program, open only to students who have been selected by the department.

Name: UF in Sardinia & Ikaria - Blue Zones: Food Culture and Longevity
About: This 6-credit program includes a 10-day* food, culture/lifestyle, and culinary experience in two of the five “Blue Zones” of the world, Ikaria, Greece, and Sardinia, Italy, where people live active and productive lives into their 90’s and beyond. You will experience the “Blue Zone” lifestyle and food habits and discover the unique flora of these beautiful islands.

Name: UF in Scandinavia - Pharmacy (PharmScan)
About: This program is reserved for PharmD students. Please contact Randall Doty for more information.

Name: UF in Senegal - African Flagship Language Initiative (French)
About: The AFLI French program is a special initiative of the Boren Awards for International Study offering awardees the opportunity for intensive language study of French and for cultural immersion by participating in domestic summer and fall overseas language programs. Proficiency of intermediate-high (ILR 1+ in Speaking) or greater is required for admission to the AFLI French program and will be verified through testing. Launched in 2014, the program aims to increase the number of Boren Scholars and Fellows engaged in the study of French language. It is sponsored by the National Security Education Program (NSEP). The summer program is administered by the University of Florida. After the summer program, students will then travel abroad to Dakar, Senegal for a full-time 2025 Fall semester of language and culture study. Requests for additional study through the 2026 spring semester can be made to Boren during the application process. All participants must complete both the summer domestic and fall abroad programs. Learning in the fall will consist of intensive small group language instruction in class and conversational sessions with language partners in a range of settings. Informal program components include home stays with local families, excursions, and cultural events. A full-time Resident Director (RD) oversees each learning center. The RD serves as a liaison between faculty, administrators, and participants, monitors the academic and cultural programs, and assists participants as they adjust (or re-adapt) to life in their host countries.

Name: UF in Seville - Spanish Language and Culture
About: Study Spanish language, literature, and linguistics in Seville, Spain. This is the only way you can earn 6 advanced Spanish credits at UF during the summer. UF in Seville is organized in conjunction with International Studies Abroad (ISA).

Name: UF in Singapore - Internship and Global Culture
About: This 8-week program is intended to allow students to undertake an internship in a global setting related to their interests or field of study while also learning about Singapore's unique history and culture. Offered by the College of Engineering and the College of Liberal Arts and Sciences, it will feature both STEM and non-STEM placements and be open to all majors. The program will offer 6 UF credits including an international internship class and a Global Culture class. Through a full-time internship students will be able to enhance their professional skills and learn to function effectively on multicultural teams. Through reflections and self-evaluations they will be able to recognize and articulate the skills they develop during the program. Through tours, excursions, and engagement with the local community, online modules, and assignments, the program will teach students about Singaporean culture and global competencies. These activities include topics such as intercultural communication, cultural values, and other aspects of intercultural learning. The program will culminate with students submitting an e-portfolio that allows them to showcase their learning in an online platform. Singapore is one of the leading global hubs for technology and business in Asia and this program will leverage Singapore’s unique position, geographically and economically, to allow students the experience of a work-integrated study abroad program.

Name: UF in Sorrento - Mediterranean Culture and Internships
About: This program will allow you to further your knowledge of European life, economy, history, & politics in a highly immersive environment. Through coursework and site visits, you will become more knowledgeable about global problems affecting the Mediterranean - Southern Italy in particular. You will analyze issues such as migration, economic trends & challenges in the European Union, religion & identity in the Mediterranean, international criminal organizations, the global causes affecting the destruction of marine ecosystems in the Mediterranean, or the impact of international tourism on small Italian communities. The internship portion of this program will specifically target the career development needs of UF students. The program will include activities & assignments to foster the integration of experiential & academic learning and to help students articulate their learning & skills digitally through the development of an electronic portfolio (personal website).

Name: UF in Sorrento - Mediterranean Culture
About: This program will allow you to further your knowledge of European life, economy, history, & politics in a highly immersive environment. Through coursework and site visits, you will become more knowledgeable about global problems affecting the Mediterranean - Southern Italy in particular. You will analyze issues such as migration, economic trends & challenges in the European Union, religion & identity in the Mediterranean, international criminal organizations, the global causes affecting the destruction of marine ecosystems in the Mediterranean, or the impact of international tourism on small Italian communities. The program will include activities & assignments to foster the integration of experiential & academic learning and to help students articulate their learning & skills digitally through the development of an electronic portfolio (personal website).

Name: UF in South Africa - Honors Scholars
About: This is a closed program, open only to Honors Program students who have been pre-selected.  If you have any questions about the application, please reach out to the study abroad advisor referenced in the Contacts below.

Name: UF in South Korea - Culture and Global Design Thinking in Engineering
About: This program offers immersive experience in Design Thinking as a tool for innovative idea and strategy development in engineering. The program is created in partnership with POSTECH, the Global Education Center for Engineers (GECE), and various industry partners in Korea. The program curriculum covers the entire framework of the design thinking process. Participants will build an understanding of the "user's need" by engaging in empathetic interactions, creating and testing rapid prototypes, and building blocks of a business case. Topics covered will include: human-centered design; needs finding; interviewing techniques; data management; ideation; and developing and testing prototypes.  UF faculty and POSTECH faculty will supervise the students.   Students will learn to function and communicate effectively in a multicultural setting, thus increasing their intercultural awareness and learning to navigate the role of engineering in a global, economic, environmental, and societal context. Weekend social programs include events pre-organized by POSTECH and Learn International (our partner on the location). These will include excursions to cultural sites, museums, and industry site visits.

Name: UF in South Korea - Global Internship & Culture
About: This six-week internship program is designed for all UF majors who wish to gain an internship experience in, Seoul, one of the most dynamic and thriving economies in East Asia. South Korea boasts an entrepreneurial, agile, and outcome-oriented corporate culture that will inspire students from all backgrounds and offer them crucial experiences that will foster their cultural understanding and business acumen. Student interns will be able to experience cosmopolitan living along the intersection of temples and rich civilization, technology, outdoors and more. The internships are conducted in English. Korean language skills s not required for this program. Intern Students receive ample onsite support from the program leaders and advisors to ensure the success of their internship program. Internship sectors include:

Name: UF in Spain and Portugal - Cultural Nutrition and Health
About: The Cultural Nutrition and Health program will provide students with an immersive overview of cultural aspects of food across the world and relationships to health and disease with a special emphasis on Spain and Portugal. Planning, implementing, and evaluating nutrition education programs for special population groups will also be integrated within course content and experiential activities. Knowledge of Spanish and Portuguese languages is not required.

Name: UF in Taiwan - Taiwanese/Chinese Culture in Place
About: Expand your worldview and enhance education by living and studying in a wide-variety of different places in Taiwan! With this program you will be exposed to a democratic Chinese speaking country that is rich with technological innovation such as microchips, and other inventions such as boba tea that have global impacts. Participants of this program will spend two weeks in the north exploring the capital city and surrounding area of Taipei, and two weeks in the more rural and picturesque southern part of the island, visiting Kaohsiung and nearby cities. Students will increase their intercultural awareness by engaging with local Taiwanese experts to gain an understanding of both city and rural life in Taiwan. Students will develop an understanding on how the Taiwanese people and Taiwanese culture relates to the rest of the world. Though the program is not designed as a language study opportunity, students will be immersed in a Chinese Mandarin speaking environment and those who are in the Chinese program will gain a deeper understanding of the language and culture of Chinese speakers. Participants will reflect on their study abroad experience and create a project upon their return to the US.

Name: UF in Tanzania - African Flagship Language Initiative (Swahili)
About: African Flagship Language Initiative (AFLI) The AFLI Swahili program is a special initiative of the Boren Awards for International Study offering awardees the opportunity for intensive language study of Swahili and for cultural immersion by participating in domestic summer and fall overseas language programs. Participants in AFLI Swahili may start with no language proficiency through advanced proficiency in Swahili. Launched in 2011, the program aims to increase the number of Boren Scholars and Fellows engaged in the study of Swahili language. It is sponsored by the National Security Education Program (NSEP). The summer program is administered by the University of Florida. After the summer program, students will then travel abroad to Usa River in Arusha, Tanzania for a full-time 2025 Fall semester of language and culture study. Requests for additional study through the 2026 spring semester can be made to Boren during the application process. All participants must complete both the summer domestic and fall abroad programs. Learning in the fall will consist of intensive small group language instruction in class and conversational sessions with language partners in a range of settings. Informal program components include home stays with local families, excursions, and cultural events. A full-time Resident Director (RD) oversees each learning center. The RD serves as a liaison between faculty, administrators, and participants, monitors the academic and cultural programs, and assists participants as they adjust (or re-adapt) to life in their host countries.

Name: UF in Tanzania - Culture and Healthcare
About: This program will introduce students to the culture and healthcare environment of two towns in Tanzania, that of lringa and Dar es Salaam. During the program, pre­health and anthropology students will encounter patients whose health problems may result from the environment in which they exist. Students will engage in real world tasks that will hopefully transform them as they work to be future physicians.

Name: UF in Tbilisi - Russian Language
About: UF in Tbilisi offers students an opportunity to make degree progress and study Russian while exploring life in one of Europe’s most fascinating countries. Students will spend their summer in the ancient, intriguing, and affordable city of Tbilisi. The program pairs 6 credits of intensive Russian language study with a homestay for an immersive language and cultural experience. Out-of-classroom excursions and special lectures and workshops introduce students to local Georgian identity, history, and current issues in contemporary Georgia. Coursework completed in Tbilisi will count toward the Russian Studies major or minor.

Name: UF in Thailand - Clinical Shadowing
About: This summer B 4-week program will provide students with a clinical shadowing experience in Bangkok, Thailand. Students will have the opportunity to shadow health professionals (25 to 30 hours per week) at government-operated Thai health clinics that are open to the public. This is a general clinical shadowing program in which students typically shadow a variety of work areas (e.g., rehabilitation, geriatrics, dentistry, fever prevention) and various stakeholders (e.g., nurses, pharmacists, primary doctors). It is unlikely that students will observe surgical procedures during this program. By the end of the program, students will be able to recognize and appreciate cultural differences in a variety of professional settings, apply concepts from their academic coursework to Thai contexts, and be more prepared to enter the professional workforce or professional school.

Name: UF in the Galapagos - Ecology Evolution and Marine Biology
About: Experience the world-famous Galapagos Islands in Ecuador. See the organisms that inspired Charles Darwin’s theory of evolution. Plunge into a marine environment like none other in the world, where iguanas dive and penguins live at the equator. Conduct self-designed research with host scientists while in-residence at the Galapagos Science Center. Visit multiple islands with the Galapagos Archipelago, seeing environments ranging from dry cactus-strewn lava fields to wet highland forests. Learn how organisms like blue footed boobies, lava lizards, marine iguanas, Darwin’s finches, and giant tortoises are uniquely adapted to live in these extreme environments. Discover how environmental threats to these unique places are being mitigated in creative ways. This 6-week Summer A program (meeting for 2 weeks on campus from 5/12-5/23 and traveling in Ecuador for 4 weeks from 5/26-6/20) offers credit for Marine Biology (4 credits) and Galapagos Ecology and Evolution (3 credits).

Name: UF in the UK - Coastal Biology Natural History & Culture
About: The coast of the United Kingdom has a remarkable history that intertwines its unique cultural and biological characteristics. This course explores coastal and nearshore maritime environments during a 3-week journey around the UK. Students will learn how the coasts were formed and adapted to by a fascinating variety of plants, animals, and human cultures. Some of these organisms and peoples are still around today while others are long gone, leaving behind only their fossilized remains or archaeological evidence. This experiential learning course will begin in London's Natural History Museum, move to the Jurassic Coast and English Channel, the southwest coast of Wales, on to northeast England and the North Sea, then finish back in London. In addition to meeting with local scientists, fishermen, and conservation specialists along the way, students will also engage with their faculty guides and fellow students from the US, Wales and England for maximum cultural immersion.

Name: UF in the UK - Exploring Science
About: Students on this program will have the opportunity to experience two different cultures (English and Scottish) while learning about some of the most groundbreaking scientific discoveries made in the U.K. No science background is required to participate, and all majors are welcome. The program will also introduce students to two universities they could later attend on exchange, for either a semester or entire academic year: the University of Glasgow and University College London. Both of these exchanges are managed by Dr. Brian Harfe, who is leading this program.

Name: UF in the UK - Health Disparities and Health Charities
About: The “Health Disparities and Health Charities” program immerses students in the history and culture of public health in the UK. Open to any major, the program helps students understand the present state of public health and medicine within the larger British context of monarchy, the slave trade, industrialization, and imperialism. Students will explore the world’s largest repository of medical archives at the Wellcome Collection in London and visit health nonprofits in Edinburgh to learn about how the third sector is researching and implementing solutions to deep-rooted health disparities in the UK. The program encourages students to draw connections between past and present and between issues of health access and equity in the UK and in their home countries. Throughout this 6,000-word-conferring program, students will have direct experience with intercultural communication and will strengthen their global awareness of public health. They will return to their home countries with research and communication skills that would empower them to advocate for health equity in their own communities. researching and implementing solutions to deep-rooted health disparities in the UK. The program encourages students to draw connections between past and present and between issues of health access and equity in the UK and in their home countries. Throughout this 6,000-word-conferring program, students will have direct experience with intercultural communication and will strengthen their global awareness of public health. They will return to their home countries with research and communication skills that would empower them to advocate for health equity in their own communities.

Name: UF in the UK - Sports & Culture
About: UF in the U.K. (Sports and Culture) is a six-credit program that immerses students in the sporting culture in the United Kingdom. It is a combination of two classes with Professor Esterline who has multiple years of professional and academic experience and a love of sports. The summer 2025 program will focus on tennis. Students will have the opportunity to immerse themselves in the tennis culture by visiting stadiums and historic venues. Students will also produce content about the local fans, towns/cities, stadiums and match day activities. Students will see and feel the real-life synergies and overlapping relationships of sports media, communications, tennis, sport and culture. They will work through conversations and an understanding of the importance of tennis and sports culture in the United Kingdom. Because the program is for four weeks, the students will also have plenty of opportunity to immerse themselves in the English culture. We intend to learn not only about tennis in the U.K. but also have the opportunity to experience London and other cities in the U.K. and all they have to offer culturally. Students will take in a holistic cultural, historical, and sporting view around the UK and work on assignments at places like Wimbledon, Stamford Bridge, Lord’s Cricket Ground, and more.

Name: UF in Utrecht - Art Business & European Studies
About: Spend six weeks in the heart of Europe with UF in Utrecht, one of UF's longest-running summer programs! This program is run in partnership with Utrecht Summerschool, Europe's largest academic summer program. UF students will participate in one of five academic tracks: The Making of Europe, History of Art, Dutch Culture, European Studies, or Innovation in European Business. You can learn more about these tracks under the 'Academics' tab of this page!

Name: UF in Valencia - Spanish Language and Culture
About: Celebrations and festivals throughout the year, like the Fallas, provide an excellent opportunity for students to witness Spanish character at its best. Study abroad in Valencia is the perfect addition to the college experience for American students! Valencia is an ideal location for travel throughout the Mediterranean, Spain, and the rest of Europe. Equidistant from Barcelona and Madrid and a short ferry ride or plane trip from the Balearic Islands of Mallorca, Ibiza, Menorca, and Formentera, Valencia’s location leaves no shortage of convenient travel possibilities. A range of architectural styles from Gothic to Modernist may be discovered. The City of Arts and Sciences (Ciudad de las Artes y las Ciencias), a museum complex and modern architectural masterpiece designed by a local architect named Santiago Calatrava, provides a prime example of modern architecture. Additionally, explore the medieval streets of the city center in the barrio del Carmen and barrio de la Seu, and don’t forget to tour the Valencia cathedral! Students will be taught a range of Spanish language practices, cooking classes, engage in cultural activities and enjoy multiple excursions.

Name: UF in Vicenza - Architecture
About: The Vicenza Institute of Architecture (VIA) Program is a semester long satellite-learning program of the University of Florida run by a rotating staff of University of Florida professors. VIA is based in Vicenza, Italy, a major center of the Veneto (the mainland region around the urban archipelago of Venice). The program focuses on evaluating and understanding the historical, social, cultural and physical aspects of this particularly rich urban context through design, research, and documentation. Lectures and presentations by local Italian educators and practicing architects augment instruction from full-time University of Florida faculty. Field trips throughout Italy and Europe further enhance your educational experience. The UF VIA Program’s fall and spring course offerings parallel those offered at the Gainesville campus, ensuring that you remain on track with your curricular requirements while studying overseas.

Name: UF in Wales - Writing in International Studies Law & Relations
About: In Cardiff, Wales, experience and take part in the legal and social transitions of a British and European capital city post-Brexit and post-EU. In this program, students will earn 6 credits. Three of these will be in ENC3254: Writing in International Studies, a 6,000-word writing course where students will research and report on a major global issue relating to the experience. Three will be through IDS4940: International Internship, for which students will take part in work study at the Cardiff Civil and Family Justice Centre, where they will work with clients and take part in legal proceedings.

Name: Universidad Adolfo Ibáñez
About: Universidad Adolfo Ibáñez (UAI) is a private, non-traditional university in Chile with over half a century of tradition in business education. The university was first created to address the absence of business education in Chile in the early 1950s. UAI originated from the Valparaiso Business School, and at that time, it was recognized as the first educational institution in Chile to offer a program in business administration. Valparaiso Business School was also considered to be a pioneer in business education among other Latin American countries, a legacy that UAI carries on today. Upon success of the business program and other accomplishments since that time, the university has expanded to include a host of academic disciplines, including Psychology, Law, and Government. More recently, the UAI is known for its focus on entrepreneurship, emphasis on practical business, and close-knit student body which allows students to develop relationships throughout their studies.

Name: Universidad Carlos III de Madrid (Business)
About: The Universidad Carlos III de Madrid (UC3M) was founded in 1989 and is a public university under the jurisdiction of the Spanish government. UC3M strives to offer high quality teaching and innovative research for the global community and is divided into three areas: the Faculty of Social Sciences; the Faculty of Humanities, Documentation and Communication; and the Higher Technical School. The university has just over 22,000 students, divided across two small campuses just outside of Madrid.

Name: Universidad Carlos III de Madrid (CLAS)
About: The Universidad Carlos III de Madrid (UC3M) was founded in 1989 and is a public university under the jurisdiction of the Spanish government. UC3M strives to offer high quality teaching and innovative research for the global community and is divided into three areas: the Faculty of Social Sciences; the Faculty of Humanities, Documentation and Communication; and the Higher Technical School. The university has just over 22,000 students, divided across two small campuses just outside of Madrid.

Name: Universidad Carlos III de Madrid (Engineering)
About: The Universidad Carlos III de Madrid (UC3M) was founded in 1989 and is a public university under the jurisdiction of the Spanish government. UC3M strives to offer high quality teaching and innovative research for the global community and is divided into three areas: the Faculty of Social Sciences; the Faculty of Humanities, Documentation and Communication; and the Higher Technical School. The university has just over 22,000 students, divided across two small campuses just outside of Madrid.

Name: Universidad de Navarra
About: The Universidad de Navarra was founded in 1952. It confers 57 undergraduate degrees through 10 schools (colleges). In 2012, the university was named one of the Top 50 Universities in the world by The New York Times. The Economist, in 2005 and 2006, ranked the University of Navarra Business School as having the best MBA in the world. Enrollment in the business school is approximately 1,000 students, including graduate and undergraduates and more than 50% of the classes are taught in English.

Name: Universidad del Norte
About: Universidad del Norte, better known as UniNorte, is a premiere university located in northern Colombia. Originally founded by group of local businessmen, this university has grown to include coursework from all academic disciplines. According to UniNorte, "The institution aims at developing its students as thinking, analytical individuals with solid ethical principles and innovative ideas that enable them to participate in an active, entrepreneurial, responsible, honest, critical and pragmatic way while contributing to the social, economic, political and cultural development of the community." This exchange program is open to students of all majors and while courses are offered in both English and Spanish, it is generally advised students have at least 4 semesters of Spanish (or equivalent) completed at the university level.

Name: Universidad del Pacifico
About: The Universidad del Pacifíco is a private university established in 1962. It has become one of the most esteemed universities in Latin America for business studies, specializing in Economics and Business Administration. Approximately 2,300 students study at this private, non-profit university, located in the safe and beautiful suburbs of Lima. Students at the UDP enjoy the benefits of a modern university, which is recognized as one of the most technologically advanced institutions in Peru.

Name: Universidad Pontificia Comillas
About: ICAI-SAPIENS at Universidad Pontificia Comillas Madrid is a program designed for engineering students interested in getting international experience without missing technical courses required for graduation with their classes. We offer a set of engineering courses, research opportunity, and a set of Spanish Culture and Language courses. Engineering courses are taught in English, while the students get immersed in the Spanish Culture through Spanish language courses and leisure activities with classmates.

Name: Universite Rennes 2 - Haute Bretagne
About: The University of Florida’s College of Liberal Arts and Science offers students the opportunity to study in Rennes, France. The University Rennes 2 is a public research university in Rennes, France, and offers a unique blend of courses in fields ranging from fine arts and literature to languages, human and social sciences, and sports science. "Our main campus is located in the heart of the city Rennes, the capital of picturesque Brittany. Our university helps contribute to regional and national dynamism through the variety of our educational offer, research and cultural vitality. Rennes itself is the 8th largest student city in France, with more than 60,000 students. While fostering local cooperation has always been a part of who we are, we also have an increasingly global perspective. With over 3,000 international students and 265 partners worldwide, our students and staff are now, more than ever, creating strong relationships with university and research institutions around the globe. Our students also benefit from an exceptional and diversified linguistic offer of 19 foreign languages. Rennes 2 is also home to the premier French-language learning center - the CIREFE". (Renne University 2 Website: Accessed on 8/13/21)

Name: University College London
About: Founded in 1826 in the heart of London, University College London (UCL) is ranked 8th in the world and is London’s leading multidisciplinary university, with more than 13,000 staff and 42,000 students from 150 different countries. UCL has always done things differently. As the first English university to champion inclusivity, diversity and open mindedness, UCL has never been afraid to rethink the norms of education and research. Their position in London brings unique benefits, providing all with access to a wealth of opportunities, and enabling UCL to contribute to everything that makes it one of the world’s greatest cities. Click here to visit the UCL Exchange student website and here to learn about International Student resources.

Name: University College Utrecht
About: Utrecht University is the Netherlands' top university, and one of the most prestigious institutions in the world. University College Utrecht (UCU) is the international liberal arts honors college of Utrecht University. It has its own campus, with it's own academic buildings and student housing. As a UF student, you are able to apply for exchange at either UCU or the main university campus; for more information on the main campus, visit our website here.

Name: University of Aberdeen
About: The University of Florida’s College of Liberal Arts and Sciences offers students the opportunity to study in Aberdeen, Scotland. The University of Aberdeen is a public research university and is the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world. It is truely an international university with 30% of their 14,500 undergraduate students being from outside of Scotland. University of Aberdeen is considered one of the seven ancient universities of Great Britain and Ireland, and it is one of the top 10 beautiful historic universities according to QS Top Universities.

Name: University of Glasgow
About: The University of Florida’s College of Liberal Arts and Sciences offers students the opportunity to study at the University of Glasgow. Founded in 1451, the University of Glasgow is the fourth oldest university in the English-speaking world. It is one of the top 100 of the world's universities and has been named Scottish University of the Year by The Times and The Sunday Times Good University Guide 2018. The university has around 28,000 undergraduate and postgraduate students, and it welcomes students from more than 140 countries worldwide. Its beautiful and historic campus makes it an ideal study location for all students.

Name: University of Graz
About: Founded in 1585, the University of Graz (Uni Graz) is Austria’s second oldest and second largest university. It has a strong international profile, with over 30,000 students and an innovative, interdisciplinary approach to research and teaching. The university is divided into six faculties, the two largest being the Faculty of Arts & Humanities and the Faculty of Natural Sciences. Its newest Faculty is that of Environmental and Regional Sciences & Education, which opened in 2007. Graz is a historic, well-preserved city that features a wide variety of architectural styles and has been awarded UNESCO World Heritage status. It is located close to Vienna and Salzburg, as well as Croatia, Switzerland, and the Czech Republic. Learn more on the Uni Graz website for incoming exchange students or view this CLAS Program Flyer.

Name: University of Leicester
About: The University of Leicester is one of the older universities in the country. Founded in 1921 with nine students, the fledgling college gained full degree-awarding powers in 1957 when it was granted its Royal Charter. The site for the University was given by a local textile manufacturer, Thomas Fielding Johnson, in order to create a living memorial for those who gave their lives in the First World War. This is reflected in the University motto 'Ut Vitam Habeant' - so that they may have life. The university established itself as a research-led university and now has a student population of close to 17,000. It has consistently ranked among the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.

Name: University of Manchester
About: The welcoming, accessible and multicultural environment that is the city of Manchester provides the ideal base for your time studying in the UK.
